{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508375"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:04:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:04:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2750"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2750"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.1,0.02,0.72,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53904"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2750"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39366"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3621"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16161"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53904"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to her psychiatrist for review of her schizophrenia treatment. Her current medication is olanzapine. She has no other significant medical conditions and does not take any other regular medications. She reports that her schizophrenia symptoms are now well controlled on olanzapine after previously trialling chlorpromazine. However, she reports gaining 20 kg over the last six months and wishes to discuss alternative treatment options.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antipsychotic medication to consider?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Quetiapine","Risperidone","Paliperidone","Aripiprazole","Clozapine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s schizophrenia symptoms are well-controlled on olanzapine, but she has experienced significant weight gain, which is a common and often intolerable side effect of this medication. It\u0027s important to address this concern to improve the patient\u0027s quality of life and reduce the risk of metabolic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAripiprazole\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice in this scenario. It is known to be weight-neutral, making it an ideal alternative for patients who have experienced significant weight gain on other antipsychotics. Aripiprazole has a unique mechanism of action as a partial dopamine agonist, which can provide effective symptom control while minimizing metabolic side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuetiapine\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Erisperidone\u003C/strong\u003E are both second-generation antipsychotics that, while effective, are associated with moderate weight gain. They would not be the best choice for this patient who is already struggling with significant weight gain from olanzapine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPaliperidone\u003C/strong\u003E is the active metabolite of risperidone and has a similar side effect profile, including the potential for weight gain. It would not offer a significant advantage over the patient\u0027s current medication in terms of metabolic effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClozapine\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for treatment-resistant schizophrenia due to its risk of severe side effects, including agranulocytosis. It is also associated with significant weight gain and metabolic disturbances, often even more so than olanzapine. It would not be an appropriate choice for this patient whose symptoms are well-controlled and who is seeking to avoid further weight gain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen changing antipsychotic medications, it\u0027s crucial to do so gradually and under close medical supervision. The transition from olanzapine to aripiprazole should be carefully managed to maintain symptom control while minimizing the risk of relapse or withdrawal effects. Additionally, lifestyle interventions such as diet and exercise should be encouraged to help manage weight, regardless of the antipsychotic medication chosen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Olanzapine has a very high risk of metabolic syndrome and this should be considered before prescribing on a long-term basis.","Aripiprazole is a weight-neutral antipsychotic and is a suitable alternative for patients experiencing significant weight gain on other antipsychotics.","Changing antipsychotic medication should be considered when patients experience intolerable side effects, even if symptoms are well-controlled."],"references":["Dayabandara M, Hanwella R, Ratnatunga S, Seneviratne S, Suraweera C, de Silva VA. Antipsychotic-associated weight gain: management strategies and impact on treatment adherence. Neuropsychiatr Dis Treat. 2017; 13: 2231-2241."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39366"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2750"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39366"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-27T15:59:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-27T16:00:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2750"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53904"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1